{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close: Circuit Analysis",
    "objective": "Synthesize Pythagoras’ Theorem and algebraic transposition to calculate circuit current from resistive and reactive components.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In practical electrical work, you will often need to combine several mathematical steps to find a final value. This usually involves using Pythagoras’ Theorem to find the total impedance (Z) of a circuit where resistance and reactance are present.",
      "Once you have the total impedance, you must then use transposition to rearrange Ohm’s Law. While the standard formula is V = I × Z, you will frequently need to isolate 'I' (Current) to determine if a circuit is operating within its design limits.",
      "Remember: to transpose, perform the inverse operation on both sides. To find the impedance, square the sides, add them, and then take the square root."
    ],
    "questionText": "An electrician has determined that a circuit has a resistance (R) of 24Ω and a reactance (X) of 7Ω. Calculate the total current (I) that will flow when the circuit is connected to a 230V supply. (Note: You must first calculate the total impedance 'Z' using Pythagoras, then transpose V = I × Z to find the current).",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "9.2",
      "9.2A",
      "9.2 Amps",
      "9.2 Amperes"
    ],
    "hint": "First, find Z by calculating the square root of (24² + 7²). Then, transpose the formula to I = V / Z and divide 230 by your result."
  }
}

